    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_95869630" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/95869630" />
    <a title="RandomAnthony" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/721021-randomanthony"><img alt="RandomAnthony" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1470919631p2/721021.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/95869630?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="RandomAnthony" class="user" itemprop="url" name="RandomAnthony" href="/user/show/721021-randomanthony">RandomAnthony</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer95869630" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14729890396360302360">I wish I was stuck in an airport with Josh Bazell’s <i>Beat the Reaper</i>, but as I wasn’t flying anywhere this week I took advantage of my nine year old’s baseball tryouts and knocked out the last third of this sucker in one sitting. The novel blends weird medical facts, a hit man in witness protection, and a narrator quickly running out of time before mafia thugs descend on the hospital in which he’s hiding. <i>Beat the Reaper</i> would make a cross-country flight feel like a commercial break; it’s not too</span>
  <span id="freeText14729890396360302360" style="display:none">I wish I was stuck in an airport with Josh Bazell’s <i>Beat the Reaper</i>, but as I wasn’t flying anywhere this week I took advantage of my nine year old’s baseball tryouts and knocked out the last third of this sucker in one sitting. The novel blends weird medical facts, a hit man in witness protection, and a narrator quickly running out of time before mafia thugs descend on the hospital in which he’s hiding. <i>Beat the Reaper</i> would make a cross-country flight feel like a commercial break; it’s not too intense but intelligent and entertaining enough to hold attention.<br /><br />Ok, ok, some of the medical scenarios, particularly the somewhat rushed final fifty pages, are completely fucking over the top. I don’t see this novel getting a film version anytime soon without a major revision of the weaponry used in the climatic defense. The novel’s strength and slight disappointment both revolve around the flippant, conversational nature of the narrator’s voice. While the quick, harried prose propels the storyline forward, nuances of the plot get lost in the intertia. Did I care? Not a whole lot. <i>Beat the Reaper</i> is fun enough to let a couple continuity issues slide. So if you’re stuck in an airport, or needing something quick and frenzied before you return to deeper material, check out <i>Beat the Reaper</i>. I finished the novel just at the end of my son’s tryouts, but had I not, I would have let him take a couple extra swings in the battle cages so I could.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14729890396360302360" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


